{
  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework, 'Context-Aware Pre-Expansion Pruning in Trie-Constrained Decoding' (CAPE), designed to enhance both the accuracy and efficiency of parallel sentence retrieval systems. In tasks like bitext mining or multilingual alignment, trie structures are commonly used to constrain generated translations to valid sentence pairs from a candidate pool. However, traditional beam search over these tries performs full expansion of child nodes before applying pruning—a computationally expensive process that evaluates many irrelevant or low-likelihood sequences. Our key insight is that pre-expansion pruning can be made reliable and effective when guided by a lightweight, learnable saliency estimator trained to predict the likelihood of a trie branch yielding high-quality output given the current decoding state and contextual embedding.\n\nThe proposed method introduces a two-stage architecture: (1) a context encoder that encodes the source sentence and partial hypothesis using a frozen pretrained multilingual model (e.g., mBERT or XLM-R), and (2) a trie-node saliency predictor—a small neural module that takes as input the hidden state of the decoder and a representation of each potential trie node (derived via attention over the remaining suffixes) to estimate its future contribution to BLEU, METEOR, or alignment score. This estimator is trained offline using reinforcement learning, where rewards are based on final retrieval accuracy and inference latency. During inference, only nodes scoring above an adaptive threshold are expanded, drastically reducing the search space.\n\nCrucially, unlike prior pruning techniques that rely solely on log-probabilities or n-gram frequencies, CAPE incorporates syntactic and cross-lingual alignment features extracted from linearized parse trees (inspired by Paper 3) to inform structural plausibility. Additionally, we integrate a self-regularization mechanism (as in Paper 1) during training of the saliency predictor to stabilize performance across varying sparsity levels, ensuring robustness even when aggressive pruning is applied. This results in faster convergence to correct sentence pairs with fewer false positives, improving both throughput and precision.\n\nThe impact of this work lies in enabling scalable, real-time parallel corpus construction for low-resource languages, where large candidate sets make exact search prohibitive. By shifting from reactive (post-expansion) to proactive (pre-expansion) pruning grounded in predictive modeling, CAPE opens a new direction in efficient constrained decoding applicable beyond retrieval—e.g., controlled generation, grammar-guided synthesis, and interactive translation.",
